<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-05T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-05T18:00:00-05:00" n="611" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d611">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/21613</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Summerlin</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-05T18:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 5, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>685. See Department’s 681, January 4, 8 p.m. You might suggest as a
                            solution of the grave Yaqui situation that Mexican Government <pb facs="0781" n="669" xml:id="pg_669"/> immediately send force of
                            approximately 5,000 troops to Sonora to restore order and garrison
                            danger points. You may intimate that you can secure passage over
                            American territory for such an expedition.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>